{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:26:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:26:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14159"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14159"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.28,0.04,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93710"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45311"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up after a recent hospital admission for heart failure. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His current medications include bisoprolol, candesartan, furosemide, dapagliflozin, and spironolactone. His most recent echocardiogram showed a left ventricular ejection fraction of 35%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He reports improvement since discharge but still has shortness of breath with moderate exertion. There is no peripheral oedema and his chest is clear to auscultation. His estimated glomerular filtration rate is 45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u003E90) and serum potassium is 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is decided that one of his medications should be replaced by another agent to improve his long-term prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would provide the greatest mortality benefit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sacubitril/valsartan","Ivabradine","Isosorbide mononitrate","Digoxin","Hydralazine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOptimising guideline-directed therapy in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF) focuses on drugs with proven mortality benefit. Replacing an angiotensin receptor blocker with an angiotensin receptor neprilysin inhibitor improves survival beyond conventional renin\u2013angiotensin system blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacubitril/valsartan\u003C/strong\u003E should replace candesartan in this patient, as it provides superior reduction in cardiovascular death and heart failure hospitalisation compared with an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker. This patient has suitable blood pressure, stable kidney function, and normal potassium, supporting the switch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIvabradine\u003C/strong\u003E can reduce heart failure admissions in people with sinus rhythm and a resting heart rate at or above 70/min despite maximally tolerated beta-blocker, but it has not demonstrated mortality benefit comparable to an angiotensin receptor neprilysin inhibitor. This patient\u0027s heart rate is 72/min and he is on a beta-blocker, but ivabradine would not exceed the mortality benefit of replacing the angiotensin receptor blocker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsosorbide mononitrate\u003C/strong\u003E may improve symptoms by reducing preload but does not reduce mortality in chronic heart failure when used alone and is reserved for symptom relief or for use with hydralazine when other pathways are unsuitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E can reduce hospitalisations and improve symptoms, particularly in people with atrial fibrillation or persistent symptoms despite optimal therapy, but it has not been shown to reduce mortality and therefore does not provide greater prognostic benefit than an angiotensin receptor neprilysin inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydralazine\u003C/strong\u003E, typically used with a long-acting nitrate when renin\u2013angiotensin\u2013aldosterone system blockade is contraindicated or not tolerated, offers less mortality benefit than an angiotensin receptor neprilysin inhibitor and is not first-line in a person tolerating an angiotensin receptor blocker.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sacubitril/valsartan provides greater mortality reduction than angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors or angiotensin receptor blockers in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction.","Disease-modifying therapy in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction should include sacubitril/valsartan, a beta-blocker, a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, and a sodium-glucose cotransporter 2 inhibitor when tolerated.","Ivabradine and digoxin reduce heart failure admissions in selected patients but do not provide mortality benefit comparable to sacubitril/valsartan."],"references":["McDonagh TA, Metra M, Adamo M, Gardner RS, Baumbach A, B\u00f6hm M, et al; ESC Scientific Document Group. 2023 Focused Update of the 2021 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure. Eur Heart J. 2023 Oct 1;44(37):3627-3639. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37622666/","Writing Committee Members; ACC/AHA Joint Committee Members. 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure. J Card Fail. 2022 May;28(5):e1-e167. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35378257/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93710"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93710"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T16:27:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T16:29:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4953"},"attributes":{"